JOHANNESBURG - The South African Social Security Agency (Sassa) is approaching the Constitutional Court to extend its contract with Cash Paymaster Services.Millions of citizens who rely on social grants may not be paid, if the contract is not extended.Sassa executive manager Raphaahle Ramokgopa said the extension of the contract carried the least risk in terms of uninterrupted service delivery.READ: Sassa allays fears on new grant payment systemThe agency was meant to find a new service provider by the 1st of April, but has failed to do so.READ: Dlamini, a no-show at Sassa Parliament briefingCash Paymaster Services is currently responsible for the distribution of R140-million in grants to 17-million beneficiaries. eNCA